From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Your Name <your.email@example.com>
Date: Tue, 03 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] ANDROID: stop_machine: single-CPU timed dump (7s) + panic
 at 10s on migration deadlock

Problem
-------
On Qualcomm platforms running Android16/GKI (Linux 6.12, Clang 19,
CONFIG_HZ=250, CONFIG_NO_HZ_IDLE=y), migration/N threads deadlock inside
multi_cpu_stop() when active_load_balance_cpu_stop() triggers a nested
stop_one_cpu_nowait() via:

  finish_task_switch()
    -> run_balance_callbacks()
      -> sched_balance_rq() OR balance_push()
        -> stop_one_cpu_nowait()   <-- re-entrancy while already executing
                                        inside stop_two_cpus / multi_cpu_stop

The Qualcomm msm_watchdog fires a bark ~10-11s later; by then crash
context (call stacks, stopper state, task list) is partially lost.

This patch (v2 vs production patch) adds two improvements requested by
the team:

  1. Single-CPU dump ownership: only ONE CPU executes the diagnostic dump.
     All other CPUs that also detect the timeout spin in cpu_relax() until
     the dump owner's panic() brings the system down. Without this, every
     non-active CPU (up to N-1 on an 8-core device) would attempt
     concurrent pr_emerg() and dump_stack() calls, interleaving output and
     corrupting the ramdump log.

  2. Timed dump with 7-second collection window followed by panic() at
     ~10 seconds from deadlock start. The original patch panicked
     immediately after the 3-second detection. This version gives the dump
     owner 7 seconds to collect all per-CPU call stacks before panicking,
     while still comfortably beating the Qualcomm bark_time of ~11 seconds.

==========================================================================
TIMELINE
==========================================================================

  T=0s    deadlock begins (active CPU stuck at ack_state(PREPARE))
  T=3s    time_after(jiffies, start + 3*HZ) fires on any spinning CPU
  T=3s    atomic_cmpxchg(&stopper_dump_owner, -1, cpu):
            ONE CPU wins ownership and enters stopper_deadlock_dump()
            ALL others: spin in cpu_relax() + touch_nmi_watchdog()
  T=3s    Sec1: outer stopper fn + caller        (fast, <100ms)
  T=3s    Sec2: multi_stop_data state dump        (fast, <100ms)
  T=3s    Sec3: cpu_online/active/dying masks     (fast, <100ms)
  T=3s    Sec4: per-CPU stopper state (lockless)  (fast, <100ms)
  T=3s    Sec5: dump_stack() on dump-owner CPU    (~100ms)
  T=3s    Sec6: trigger_all_cpu_backtrace()
              In PREPARE deadlock ALL CPUs have IRQs ON.
              IPI response is fast (microseconds).
              ktime deadline guards the 6-second budget:
                ktime_deadline = ktime_get() + 6000ms
              If any CPU is unexpectedly non-responsive the ktime
              guard prevents this section from exceeding T=9s.
  T=9s    Sec7: show_state() -- SysRq-T equivalent (~500ms)
  T~10s   stopper_deadlock_dump() returns
  T~10s   panic() called by dump owner
  T=11s   Qualcomm bark_time (worst case, ~1s margin)

  Non-owner CPUs: spin at position C with touch_nmi_watchdog() so the
  NMI watchdog does not fire independently and corrupt the dump.
  Owner's panic() delivers them to the panic handler.

==========================================================================
Why IRQs are ON during the entire dump window
==========================================================================

The PREPARE-state deadlock keeps IRQs ON on ALL CPUs:

  - Non-active CPUs: stuck at position C in PREPARE state.
    multi_cpu_stop() has not yet called local_irq_disable()
    (that only happens on state transition to DISABLE_IRQ).
    -> IRQs ON -> jiffies tick -> time_after() fires correctly.

  - Active CPU: stuck trying to ack_state(PREPARE) while waiting
    for nested stop work.  IRQs ON in this state.

Because IRQs are ON when stopper_deadlock_dump() runs:
  - ktime_get() reads hardware counter correctly.
  - trigger_all_cpu_backtrace() IPI reaches all CPUs without the
    10s-per-CPU timeout hazard (CPUs ARE interrupt-capable).
  - touch_nmi_watchdog() actually works.
  - pr_emerg() / printk() flush normally.

Compare: DISABLE_IRQ/RUN states have IRQs OFF.  jiffies are frozen.
time_after() returns false.  The detection cannot fire in those states.
This is the IRQ-off false-positive guard -- intentional by design.

==========================================================================
Single-CPU dump ownership design
==========================================================================

Problem with N-1 CPUs simultaneously dumping:
  - Concurrent dump_stack() calls = interleaved, unreadable output
  - Concurrent show_state() = duplicate/corrupted task list
  - Concurrent pr_emerg() may overflow the kernel log ring buffer
  - Multiple CPUs calling panic() race on panic_lock spinlock

Solution: atomic_cmpxchg(&stopper_dump_owner, -1, (int)cpu)
  - stopper_dump_owner initialized to -1 (sentinel = no owner).
  - First CPU to reach position C after timeout calls cmpxchg.
  - On success (old == -1): this CPU owns the dump.
  - On failure (old != -1): another CPU already owns it.
    Non-owner sets timed_out=1, enters while(1) cpu_relax() loop,
    calls touch_nmi_watchdog() every iteration.
    Owner's panic() will bring all CPUs down together.

stopper_dump_owner is declared as a module-scope static atomic so it
is visible to all CPUs simultaneously and persists across loop iters.

==========================================================================
Fix 1: int cpu -> unsigned int cpu (retained from production patch)
==========================================================================

smp_processor_id() returns 'unsigned int'. The original 'int cpu' is a
pre-existing type mismatch against cpumask_test_cpu(unsigned int, ...) and
per_cpu_ptr(..., unsigned int). Clang 19 warns at every call site via
-Wsigned-unsigned-enum-conversion. 'err' retains int because msdata->fn()
can return negative error codes.

==========================================================================
Fix 2: Position C unconditional detection (retained from production patch)
==========================================================================

The detection is placed AFTER the closing brace of the else-if block:

  do {
    if (curstate < msdata->state) { curstate = ...; switch ... }
    if (is_active)
        ack_state(msdata);                   /* A */
    else if (curstate > MULTI_STOP_PREPARE) {
        touch_nmi_watchdog();
        rcu_momentary_eqs();                 /* B */
    }
    /* C: unconditional, ALL CPUs, ALL states */
    if (!timed_out &&
        time_after(jiffies, start_jiffies + STOPPER_TIMEOUT_JIFFIES)) {
        ...
    }
  } while (curstate != MULTI_STOP_EXIT);

Position B is unreachable in PREPARE state (curstate == PREPARE, condition
is false). Position C is reached by ALL CPUs in ALL states every iteration.
In DISABLE_IRQ/RUN: jiffies frozen -> time_after() false -> no fire.

==========================================================================
New include: linux/ktime.h
==========================================================================

ktime_get() is used for the 7-second dump window.  ktime_t and ktime_get()
are declared in <linux/ktime.h>.  The function reads the hardware monotonic
counter directly and does NOT depend on IRQ-driven jiffies -- correct for
use inside the dump window where we need real elapsed time.

==========================================================================
Build fixes (retained from production patch)
==========================================================================

[FIX-A] dump helpers placed AFTER struct multi_stop_data.
        Inserting before struct multi_stop_data causes Clang 19 to treat
        'struct multi_stop_data' in function parameters as a new forward
        declaration, triggering [-Werror,-Wvisibility].

[FIX-C] Deadlock detection at position C (unconditional), not inside
        the else-if block (position B). The else-if closing brace must
        be a CONTEXT line, not an added line.

==========================================================================
Android GKI compliance
==========================================================================

- Single file: kernel/stop_machine.c only
- No new exported symbols, no new Kconfig options
- Clang 19 / LLD 19 compatible
- atomic_cmpxchg(): <linux/atomic.h> via kernel.h -- already included
- ktime_get(): <linux/ktime.h> -- newly added include
- trigger_all_cpu_backtrace(): <linux/nmi.h> already in stop_machine.c
- show_state(): <linux/sched/debug.h> -- always present in GKI
- jiffies / HZ / time_after(): unconditionally available

